Handlers?

Handler is a task that runs only when notified by another task that reported a change — not on every playbook run. 
It's commonly used for restarting services only when their config file actually changes, avoiding unnecessary restarts.

Handler = Task that runs only when notified (triggered by a change).

Simple analogy:

Doorbell — only rings when someone presses it, not all the time.

Problem without Handler:

tasks:
  - name: copy config
    copy:
      src: nginx.conf
      dest: /etc/nginx/

  - name: restart nginx
    service:
      name: nginx
      state: restarted   # restarts EVERY time playbook runs
                         # even if config didn't change ❌

Solution with Handler:

tasks:
  - name: copy config
    copy:
      src: nginx.conf
      dest: /etc/nginx/
    notify: restart nginx    # trigger handler only if file changed

handlers:
  - name: restart nginx
    service:
      name: nginx
      state: restarted       # runs ONLY if config changed ✅

How it works:

Copy config → file changed?
      ├── YES → notify handler → restart nginx ✅
      └── NO  → skip handler → no restart ✅

